{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1252\deff0\deflang1033{\fonttbl{\f0\fnil\fcharset0 Microsoft Sans Serif;}}
{\colortbl ;\red0\green0\blue0;}
{\*\generator Msftedit 5.41.15.1515;}\viewkind4\uc1\pard\cf1\b\f0\fs20 XML documents do not contain an index. The elements are stored in some order, but there is no provision for sorting them.\par
\par
However, Magic will handle indexing for XML documents just as it would for any Data source. All that you need to do is to specify the indexing you want to use, by creating an alternate index in the XML view.\par
\par
In addition, you can create a Task Sort to sort the level locally in one task. This is useful when creating reports, where the index is not needed often.\par
\par
Press the Contacts button to view the Contacts XML View. From that view, you can use the runtime sort and index options to change the display order.\par
}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1252\deff0\deflang1033{\fonttbl{\f0\fnil\fcharset0 Microsoft Sans Serif;}{\f1\fswiss\fprq2\fcharset0 Microsoft Sans Serif;}}
{\colortbl ;\red0\green0\blue0;\red255\green0\blue128;}
{\*\generator Msftedit 5.41.15.1515;}\viewkind4\uc1\pard\cf1\b\f0\fs20 1. \i\f1 Alternate keys\i0\f0 : Select \cf2 Options->View by Key\cf1  to select from the Alternate Indexes that have been set up for the Contacts view.\par
\par
2. \i\f1 Sort records\i0\f0 : Select \cf2 Options->Sort Records\cf1  to create your own custom Sort.\par
\par
3. \i\f1 Click on the table headers\i0\f0 . All the columns have the \cf2 Sortable\cf1  property set to Yes.\par
}

{\rtf1\ansi\ansicpg1252\deff0\deflang1033{\fonttbl{\f0\fnil\fcharset0 Microsoft Sans Serif;}}
